SUMMARY:Ethics - Week 2: Welfare v. Duty - Utilitarian & Deontological Perspectives
DESCRIPTION:EWMBA 207 - Ethics & Responsible Business Leadership\nProf. Jonathan Weigel\n\nWeek 2 (Blue): Monday April 6\, 2026\n6:00-9:30 PM PT\n\nTopic: Welfare v. Duty: Utilitarian and Deontological Perspectives on Ethics\n\nObjectives:\n- Managerial domain: Non-market strategy challenges in the global economy\n- Consequentialist Ethics (Utilitarianism): Maximize well-being of a specified group\n- Deontological Ethics (Duty-based): Rights and duties\n- Managerial application: Human Resources - gender asymmetries in organizational life\n\nPreparation Guidelines:\n- How would a utilitarian evaluate the dilemma facing Ziqitza's leadership?\n- "When in Rome\, do as the Romans do." Should you always play by local rules? Act vs. Rule Utilitarianism?\n- Is it right to sacrifice the individual for the collective? Always\, sometimes\, or never?\n- Do businesses have a responsibility to create an inclusive work environment if it doesn't maximize welfare or profits?\n- Should romantic relationships among members of the same organization be forbidden?\n\nRequired Readings:\n- Smith and Crawford: Ziqitza Health Care Limited: Responding to Corruption\n- Vaccaro: Dirty dancing\, Too much drinking\n- Velasquez: Utilitarianism (60-71)\n- Marcus and Kaiser: Deontological Ethics - Rights and Duties\n- Le Guin: Those who walk away from Omelas\n\nOptional:\n- Awad et. al. (2018) / The Moral Machine Experiment\n- O'Neill / A Simplified Account of Kant's Ethics\n\nCourse Page: https://bcourses.berkeley.edu/courses/1550881
LOCATION:N370 Chou Hall
URL;VALUE=URI:https://bcourses.berkeley.edu/courses/1550881
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
