SUMMARY:Ethics - Week 4: Environmental Justice & Ethics of Training Generative AI
DESCRIPTION:EWMBA 207 - Ethics & Responsible Business Leadership\nProf. Jonathan Weigel\n\nWeek 4 (Blue): Monday April 20\, 2026\n6:00-9:30 PM PT\n\nTopic: Environmental Justice and the Ethics of Training Generative AI\n\nObjectives:\n- Managerial application: Inequality\, equity\, sustainability\n- Environmental Justice: Market-based mechanisms (pollution rights) and asymmetric outcomes across social groups\n- Generative AI: Trade-off between data for effective AI models and property rights of content creators\n\nPreparation Guidelines:\n- What are the motives of opponents/proponents of market mechanisms to resolve environmental challenges? Do their claims have a rigorous ethical defense?\n- Are market-based mechanisms discriminatory? Are they fair?\n- Assess the fairness of the pollution credits trading system. Would your assessment differ if you lived in a hotspot?\n- Whose property rights are at stake in the debate over training generative AI models and IP?\n- Would an act and rule utilitarian agree or disagree about the ethics of training generative AI without licensing agreements?\n\nRequired Readings:\n- Dal Bo\, Weigel\, and Xu: Cap-and-Trade Meets Environmental Justice in Richmond\, CA\n- Dal Bo\, Weigel\, and Xu: The Ethics of Training Generative AI Models\n\nOptional:\n- Fears and Dennis: This is environmental racism\n- The Economist: Environmental Justice in the Balance\n- The Economist: Generative AI is a marvel. Is it also built on theft?\n- Menand: Is A.I. the Death of I.P.? (The New Yorker)\n\nCourse Page: https://bcourses.berkeley.edu/courses/1550881
LOCATION:N370 Chou Hall
URL;VALUE=URI:https://bcourses.berkeley.edu/courses/1550881
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
