SUMMARY:Ethics - Week 5: Corporate Social Responsibility & Gene Editing
DESCRIPTION:EWMBA 207 - Ethics & Responsible Business Leadership\nProf. Jonathan Weigel\n\nWeek 5 (Blue): Monday April 27\, 2026\n6:00-9:30 PM PT\n\nTopic: Corporate Social Responsibility and Gene Editing\n\nObjectives:\n- Managerial application: Corporate Social Responsibility\, ethical challenges from scientific progress\n- Contrast traditional leadership with leadership in economic ecosystems\n- Address who "owns" the firm\n- Apply frameworks to CRISPR and gene editing\n\nPreparation Guidelines:\n- Should firms do everything they can to "do good\," only certain things\, or none?\n- Do shareholders own firms\, and should managers maximize share value?\n- Do you think CSR can be defined meaningfully beyond legal compliance?\n- Consider the situation from Dr. He's position. What paths of action are available?\n- Would a virtuous choice involve other considerations? Which?\n- Who are the relevant actors\, and what are the stakes involved in pursuing gene editing?\n\nRequired Readings:\n- Dal Bo\, Weigel and Xu: CRISPR and the Selfish Gene Editor\n- Friedman: The Social Responsibility of Business is to Increase its Profits\n- Detert: Managing yourself: Cultivating everyday courage\n\nOptional:\n- Fisher / Dimmock: Aristotelian Virtue Ethics - Introduction\n- Pinker: The Moral Instinct\n- Haidt: The New Synthesis in Moral Psychology\n\nAssignment Due Today:\n- Assignment 4: My Experience Revisited (graded)\n\nOptional Exam Prep (due midnight before Final):\n- Assignment 5: Sustainable Supply Chains\n\nCourse Page: https://bcourses.berkeley.edu/courses/1550881
LOCATION:N370 Chou Hall
URL;VALUE=URI:https://bcourses.berkeley.edu/courses/1550881
STATUS:CONFIRMED
END:VEVENT
